			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: AA path<a name="19964"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 9 04 1:00 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Depends entirely on how you like to play.
<br />

<br />
If you raid a lot, you've already heard the right answer.  IM &amp; EN are essential.  The benefits they provide, leveraged over a 50-75 person raid are huge.
<br />

<br />
If you don't raid a lot, the answer may be different for you.  For example, I have IM2 and don't plan on getting IM3 for some time.  Yes, it'd be an improvement for me, but leveraged only over a 6 person group, the marginal boost IM3 provides isn't worth 9 points to me yet.
<br />

<br />
Things to think about:
<br />

<br />
1.  Everyone says Fading Memories is your top priority, and everyone is right.  This is, hands down, our best AA.  If you need documentation on why it dominates, read around on the various forums &amp; you'll see tons of posts praising its utility.
<br />

<br />
Big thing with Fade is that it's a quantum leap of power for you for relatively few points.  Unlike everything else, Fade isn't just a marginal improvement at something you already do -- Fade is an entirely new ability that opens up entirely new strategies for you.
<br />

<br />
2.  I got Mental Clarity 3 and never looked back.  Folks may disagree with this.  I am usually our puller, though, and I find that I can never have too much mana regen.  In fact, if I wasn't saving for the GoD runspeed AA, I'd likely sink my banked points into getting the Archetype regen to level 3 so I can buy the Mind &amp; Body Regen class ability.  
<br />

<br />
That said, I like to fade a LOT so I'm a psycho for mana regen.  I'm currently at FT7 and saving LDON points until I hit FT15.  You can pull successfully with much much less -- I just prefer to do it my way.
<br />

<br />
3.  Again, assuming you do a lot of pulling, look seriously at Boastful Bellow.  Handy for several things:  A.  It's an instant pulling tool -- helps squeeze the maximum value out of lulls.  Using BB to pull, I can keep lull on more mobs.  B.  It makes relocating a mezzed mob easier.  I tend to pull 2 mobs, mez one as I'm running back in, transfer agro on the other, and then go back and finish bringing the first in.  Bellow is handy for that.  C.  It's also handy as yet another way to interrupt casting.  Nice that it's instant -- if you save it, and it doesn't look like you'll get mez or Saryn's off in time, you can always bellow at a gater or chealer.  Doesn't always work, but sometimes it does.
<br />

<br />
4.  If your role in the group involves a lot of meleeing, the offensive AAs do increase your DPS substantially.  I have Ambi &amp; Harmonious Attack 5 and love 'em.  Thinking seriously about doing Combat Fury to 3 and Fury of the Ages, although Sinister Strikes from GoD looks like more DPS for the points atm.  These are nothing to sneeze at.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
